name: ethyl (4-chloro-2,6-dinitrophenyl)carbamate
source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-1900
Reason: To predict the melting point of ethyl (4-chloro-2,6-dinitrophenyl)carbamate, we consider the functional groups and their effects on the basic phenyl ring structure. The basic phenyl ring (as found in benzene) typically has a melting point around 5.5 degrees Celsius. Chlorine substituent: Approximately +40 degrees due to increased molecular weight and polarity. Each nitro group: +80 degrees due to the strongly electron-withdrawing nature, which stabilizes the crystal lattice through intermolecular interactions. Two nitro groups are present, so this effect is doubled. Carbamate group (ethoxycarbonylamino): +30 degrees, given its ability to engage in hydrogen bonding and resonance stabilization, further enhancing lattice stability. Therefore, considering these adjustments sequentially, we predict an increased melting point for the target compound as follows: 5.5 (phenyl ring) + 40 (chlorine) + 2 * 80 (nitro groups) + 30 (carbamate) = 235.5 degrees Celsius.
